				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Is Slack Really Worth $2.8 Billion? A Conversation With Stewart Butterfield</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Farhad Manjoo			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-04-16T22:27:02+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">April 16, 2015 6:27 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">April 16, 2015 6:27 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/04/16/is-slack-really-worth-2-8-billion-a-conversation-with-stewart-butterfield/" data-title="Is Slack Really Worth $2.8 Billion? A Conversation With Stewart Butterfield" data-description="The corporate messaging start-up Slack raised $160 million at a $2.8 billion valuation. Stewart Butterfield, the company&#039;s chief executive, discusses Silicon Valley&#039;s easy-money moment.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/04/16/technology/16bits-slack/16bits-slack-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/04/16/technology/16bits-slack/16bits-slack-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/04/16/technology/16bits-slack/16bits-slack-blog480.jpg" id="100000003633324" width="480" height="305" alt="Stewart Butterfield, chief executive of Slack, in the company&#039;s office in San Francisco."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="305"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Stewart Butterfield, chief executive of Slack, in the company's office in San Francisco.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Jason Henry for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When I <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/12/technology/slack-the-office-messaging-app-that-may-finally-sink-email.html">recently wrote</a> about Slack, a corporate messaging app that has aspirations to replace email, investors valued the company at $1 billion. That was a month ago. Today, the start-up announced that it has raised $160 million from a half dozen investors, and that it is now worth $2.8 billion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Slack, which is just a year old, has more than 750,000 daily active users, 200,000 of whom are paying customers. By many estimates, it is the fastest-growing business applicationÂ of all time.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Still, Slackâs escalating valuation in such a short time seems destined to spark questions about the rising possibility of a tech bubble. I askedÂ Stewart Butterfield, Slackâs co-founder and chief executive, about the company, its growth and the bubble in a wide-ranging conversation this morning.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Iâm surprised that youâre raising money, because last time we talked you said that you had enough money.</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Do you have enough money?</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">No. But itâs not free money, right?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Itâs pretty straightforward. Iâve been in this industry for 20 years. This is the best time to raise money ever. It might be the best time for any kind of business in any industry to raise money for all of history, like since the time of the ancient Egyptians. Itâs certainly the best time for late-stage start-ups to raise money from venture capitalists since this dynamic has been around.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And as a board member and a C.E.O., I have a responsibility to our employees, to our customers. And as a fiduciary, I think it would be almost imprudent for me not to accept $160 million bucks for 5-ish percent of the company when itâs offered on favorable terms.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We donât have an immediate use for that money. But it increases the value of our stock and can allow potential employees to take our offers, and it reinforces the perception for our larger customers that weâll be around for the long haul. All of that stuff.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Is there any downside?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Did you watch the <a href="//artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/04/12/silicon-valley-season-2-premiere-recap/">last episode of &#8220;Silicon Valley&#8221;</a>? For a company thatâs very early stage â their product isnât necessarily out, they donât know if their business model is going to work, they donât know what conversion rates and retention rates are going to be like â it can be fairly high risk. Weâve seen that in the past. A new company before it has even started has achieved a high valuation, and that hasnât worked out well.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But itâs not really a factor at this stage. Growth has been unprecedented. Itâs crazy. So I think thereâs less downside risk here.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The market could turn, and the kinds of valuations you get from V.C. investors might not be as favorable in six months or a year. But on the other hand, we will have a couple hundred million dollars in the bank, and thatâs a great position to be in.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Are you saying that having the money in the bank in case the V.C. market turns bad â was that a primary reason to raise it?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Itâs one of the best reasons. Letâs say we were a gold-mining business, or maybe just a person who had a whole bunch of gold. And gold prices are going crazy. Selling some of the gold now, so you have cash in the bank in case things change in the future, is not a bad idea.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Itâs a hedge, and a hedge thatâs unbelievably good for us. Itâs a lot of money. In the case where everything turns to [expletive], we will look pretty smart.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Youâve said before that valuations are âarbitrary.â Is Slackâs almost $3 billion valuation arbitrary?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Public investors often have some underlying rationale for getting to a decent price. In this market, there are bets about how big the companyâs market can be, how good the team is â but there is also just a whole lot of supply and demand.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And there are a lot of investors who have a lot of money. So when I say arbitrary, I mean that itâs not coming from some airtight, textbook formula for how to value these types of companies. Itâs based on how many there are â and thereâs only one Slack â and if you would like to invest in this Slack, this is the price that it costs.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Itâs very highly influenced by other factors: Interest rates being low, thereâs a lot of money in V.C., funds get larger as a result, but the number of deals that they do remains about the same. So therefore the amount that they invest per deal goes up, which means the valuation goes up.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So do you think Slack is worth $3 billion?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It is, because people say it is.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Iâm not trying to be trite, and I know why youâre asking, but if you go down to the fundamental level, we all have an agreement about what things are worth â until we donât.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Maybe the better question is, how great is the risk that the consensus about what Slack is worth will change dramatically?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There is a risk that investors will say, maybe this company, at this time, is only worth half what we thought. But since we came back from the holidays, everything doubled. Thatâs a crazy rate of growth, but it has remained constant since we launched. We canât keep that forever â the law of large numbers, weâll start to saturate markets. But obviously weâre not there yet. I donât feel like there are any serious vulnerabilities in the business. So I think even if our valuation were to go down, it would go down until we catch up to it.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So itâs a great time to be raising money as a founder. But if you were looking at the tech economy from a different perspective, would you still say itâs a good thing that itâs so easy to raise money?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Iâd say itâs probably good. The odds of new companies doing interesting things getting started would go up. Iâm sure that it can have some bad effects in the sense of distorting young foundersâ perceptions about what their companies should be worth, and frustrating their expectations, potentially. And there are knock-on effects that are bad â pressures on salaries, pressure on rents. We signed a lease on our San Francisco office at $62 a square foot, and we sublet it at $75, nine months later. And down in Palo Alto, people are paying $120 per square foot, and not even fancy offices. And itâs not a great thing, necessarily, for our local economy.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But is it a great thing for the world? Youâre getting a whole bunch of money you donât really need that you probably wonât use. What is the use of giving you $160 million that youâre just going to keep in the bank for a rainy day?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Eventually, we will find a use for it, at least I hope we do. Now, as opposed to this money being used to house the homeless or feed starving children â but thatâs not where this money would otherwise go. This is investment capital. One could certainly make the argument that investment capital has inflated out of proportion to the rest of the economy. But itâs not like if they hadnât given the money to us, they would have given to a homeless person instead.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But the reason people outside of tech look at a story like a year-old company being valued at $3 billion is that they wonder, what if youâre wrong? What if your growth is an illusion and it wonât continue? Or what if thereâs something else youâre missing? And not just you, but a whole bunch of other companies like you that have been raising money so fast. Do you worry about that â that there may be some kind of systemic problem?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yes and no. As a citizen, I donât think it would be a really bad thing in the end if all these investors lose a great deal of money, because itâs really not a very large percentage of the overall economy. Iâm <a href="//fortune.com/2015/04/10/brainstorming-with-marc-andreessen/">quoting Marc Andreessen here</a>: The entire amount of V.C. funding that happened last year was $50 billion. Thatâs compared to the total market of share buybacks and dividends by public companies in the U.S. being $1 trillion. So itâs one-twentieth of the overall public market dynamics, which is a small percentage of the overall economy, so itâs not going to make a difference to most private citizens whether V.C.s lose a lotÂ of money here.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It does make a difference to me personally in that sense that it matters what happens to our employees, partners and the investors that I work with directly.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So what are the possible things you can do with this money?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Acquisitions would be one. Advertising could be another. We may want to be able to spend beyond our means to grow the business. Itâs nice to have all kinds of options. We might have to defend ourselves against predators. We might find opportunities to do something better or faster that requires capital. At some point weâll start advertising, and letâs say advertising is effective for us â so we may put tens of millions of dollars into it. Iâm not saying thatâs what weâll do, but itâs nice to have the option.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So you go out and raise money and you donât have to tell the investors what itâs for?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Nope. They want to own some of the company, and they believe it will be worth more in the future. And thatâs it.</p>
